nMedicalCenter,reportedlytheKimfamily’spersonalhospital.Thatarticlecited“NorthKoreansources,”butacorrectionissuedthesameday—afterthearticle’sviralreceptiononline—clarifiedthattheinformationhadcomefromonlya“singleDailyNKsource”insidetheDPRK.MostofthemedicalstaffreturnedtoPyongyangonApril19afterKim’shealthimproved,thearticlesaid,but“afewremainandarecontinuingtomonitorhisrecovery.”ThearticlewaspickedupinEnglishbyReutersandthenCNNthesameday—andwithinhourshadbecomeoneofthebiggeststoriesintheworld.TheCNNarticleadditionallyclaimedthatU.S.intelligencewasmonitoringreportsthatKimwasin“gravedanger”aftersurgery.ButCNN’sarticlealsochangedafterpublication:theoriginalheadlineread,“U.S.Source:NorthKoreanleaderingravedangeraftersurgery.”Itwaseventuallychangedtothemoretentative“U.S.monitoringintelligencethatNorthKoreanleaderisingravedangeraftersurgery.”Bythen,wordthatKimJongUnmaybeincapacitated,orevendead,wasalreadyspreadingaroundtheworld.Inasignofjusthowquicklythesekindsofrumorscanspread,oneHongKongmediaexecutive,QinFeng,postedamessageonWeibocontainingjusttwocandleemojis.Forsome,themessage—nowdeleted—wasproofenoughthatKimhaddied.“IstheKimnewsreal?QinFengpostedcandlesonWeibo,”askedoneChinese-languageuseronTwitter.“Let’sseehowmanyhoursit’llbeuntiltheofficialannouncement,”QinsaidinalongerWeibopostthatwasalsodeleted.“Ineverpostfakeinformation.”QinisthenieceofformerChineseforeignministerLiZhaoxing.TheChinese-languageWorldJournalreferredtoQinFeng’sWeibopostsasacrediblesignthatKimhadreallydied,andtheDutchnewspaperDeTelegraafcitedthe“topHongKongSatelliteTelevisionfigure’s”claimsaswell.Insomeforeignpublications,asifplayingagameoftelephone,QinFengbecameanunidentified“HongKongsource.”TherumoraboutKimJongUn’sdeath,however,stayedthesame.FALSEIMAGESSomeoutletsturnedtomorestraightforwardvideoandphotomanipulations.WidelysharedfakevideosandimageswithJapanesesubtitlesalsoappeartoshowKimJongUn’sfuneraldisplay,withNorthKorea’sfamousnewsannouncerRiChunHeedressedinablackhanbokannouncingKim’sdeath.Onevide